[5] Guadeloupe
Date: Wed 2 Jun 2010
Source: France Antilles [in French, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
<http://www.guadeloupe.franceantilles.fr/regions/departementales/dengue-650-cas-par-semaine-02-06-2010-81079.php>

The latest newsletter from the Institut de Veille Sanitaire reports
650 new infections of the dengue virus during the week of 17-23 May
2010. The epidemic remains at a high level, very high: 650 is 8 times
the maximum number of infections expected in this period.

The total number of affected people since the beginning of the
epidemic (the 1st week of December [2009]) now stands at 7260. Since
the beginning of the epidemic 106 laboratory confirmed cases have been
hospitalized. There are 50 common [dengue disease] types, 19 severe, 4
of DHF (or shock syndrome), and 19 incomplete [sic] hemorrhagic forms.
The remaining 14 cases are being classified. The distribution of cases
among adults and children is about 50/50.

Over the past 2 weeks, the Mussel community and those in St Francis
are the highest impacted on Grande Terre. The epidemic is also present
in the region and North Pointoise Grande-Terre. On Basse-Terre, [these
are islands in the archipelago of Guadeloupe. - Corr.SB] high
incidences of the disease are now observed at Three Rivers and Terre
de Haut, while the epidemic continues in Sous-le Vente and Santa Rosa.

--
