[10] Brazil (general)
Date: Tue 1 Jun 2010
Source: Destak [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.destakjornal.com.br/readContent.aspx?id=14,60776>


Dengue cases in Brazil are increasing among the youngest population,
those of less than 15 years of age. Because of this, the Ministry of
Health now fears that dengue will turn into a "childhood disease", as
has occurred in Southeast Asia. Data from the Ministry, noted in the
Sao Paulo file, show that as of 2007 children were practically not
presenting with dengue. Today, the mean has risen to one child for
every 4 adults.

This shift occurs because, after a person is bitten [infected], that
person is immune to the virus that infected him or her. Since there
are 4 types of [dengue] virus, after successive epidemics, the adult
population becomes protected and the children are the easier [more
susceptible] population.

Also according to the survey, in the [dengue] epidemic of 2008 in Rio
de Janeiro, most patients were less than 15 years of age. The
difference [between Brazil and Southeast Asia] is that [dengue]
epidemics have been occurring in Southeast Asia for 60 years and in
Brazil, for only 20. Because of this, the shift will take longer to
happen [in Brazil].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[Nelson Rodrigues, a renowned Brazilian journalist, author, and
playwright had an expression that fits well here, the "blindingly
obvious". [This age shift] looks like a fantastic, unpredictable
discovery. It is not. The shift of dengue to younger ages was foreseen
for over a decade. Sad but true. - Mod.LJS]

[Re: "Today, the mean has risen to one child for every 4 adults" -- or
1 in 2 in Rio. The question is not why is dengue apparently more
common in children in Brazil now than it used to be, but that given
half the pop. of Brazil is aged less than 15, why have not half the
cases been in children since the beginning? Exposure to mosquito
bites in and around houses must have been similar to that of adults.
Perhaps dengue cases in children were much milder and unreported
previously. - Mod.JW]
